If my interpretation isn't too far off, I think MarkIX brings up a valuable point in that if a military works against the will of the people, i.e. is just a tool of government oppression deployed against the populace, than there is little reason we should trust what the expressed sentiments of such a populace might be since it's likely coerced and we therefore can't determine what they are really feeling.  In essence, the people of a free, democratic society are far more likely to come to reasonable decisions since they have to the freedom to look at issues from all sides, and from that comes the moral authority when deciding military action.  That's my take anyway.  It's late so hopefully I'm not too far off.       <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=markix@nuclearspace>MarkIX</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Tourist</span><br>  Posts: 4<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/19/03 2:50 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=787.topic&index=24>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Armed Forces</span><hr size=1> Timberwind<br>
